Here's what a &quot;double standard&quot; is to a troll:

Joe:    Linux is this, Microsoft is that.
Bill:    Linux is that, Microsoft is this!
Nad-hor:    Double standard!  Double standard!
Whoop!  Whoop!  Whoop!

Hell, even after years of DEC and HP &quot;minicomputers&quot;, I spent a couple
decades developing (application) code almost exclusively for DOS and
Windows.  And I used DOS and Windows for doing (amateurish) MIDI music.

So I was a &quot;Windows user&quot;, and &quot;Windows programmer&quot;, even though I had a
background (not very deep) in UNIX, DEC's RSX-11 and RT-11, and HP's
RTE-IV, and hence didn't have a very high opinion of DOS or Windows.

Ironically, just as Windows started becoming at least a shade of what
Bill Gates endearingly, if laughably, called &quot;the UNIX killer&quot;, I
discovered Linux, and could now afford a machine with something akin
to my favorite OS on it.  And not only that, the developer community
was/is even more open than Microsoft's community (there was a time when
it costs real money to learn anything), and so it was much
easier to dig deeper, and actually get into some system's programming.
In the process I've learned more about UNIX and computing in general,
and learnt most of it running Linux machines.

Of course, that's just my path, and I don't really believe most Windows
users are dumb -- it's really that most computer users aren't very
experienced with the paradigm, and their OS provides nice deep pits with
spikes coated with malware.

Microsoft and Windows do have some nice technology, and if they were
more open about it, and less homicidal to the interests of others, they
could be real contributors to open-source.  Of course, the company's
main interest is business, which is somewhat crippling to the more open
interests of the programmers there, I think.

As for the trolls?  Idiots and assholes, even if they score a point now
and then.

