Yes I made money, but unlike you I don't feel the need to brag about it
every minute of the day. IMCE the type of people who brag about money
are invariably those who never had any, i.e. the nuevo riche, and the
motivation for bragging is usually the fear of losing it.

I hate to burst your bubble, but making money is not the pinnacle of
human achievement, and like they say - you can't take it with you when
you die. If your best accomplishment in life is &quot;making money&quot; then you
must lead a very sad existence. So tell me DooFy, what will /you/ be
remembered for?

As for me, yes I did earn a living. /Shock horror/ yes I made money. Can
you believe it? I actually went out and /worked/ for a living, and
people had the audacity to /pay/ me for the privilege. Incredible but
true. Even more incredible ... I then took that money and /invested/ it,
in Unit Trusts no less. Good grief, earning money *and* investing it,
what is the world coming to?

But here's what I didn't do; I didn't screw people over, I didn't sell
them something that lacked integrity, I didn't extort money out of
people or blackmail them, I didn't lie to them, in fact I didn't expect
them to do anything that wasn't entirely justified. In my work (at
least) my life has been entirely ethical. I earned every penny.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; working on proprietary software
">

First, I didn't &quot;work on&quot; any software, I merely took the clients
specifications, passed them back to the office, received the completed
packages, installed them, restored backup data, integrated the new
system with several existing support systems, monitored and tuned the
systems, engaged in several meetings with the client, took notes, wrote
several reports, and came home. At no time did I /create/ any software
(discounting scripts).

As for it being proprietary software, it was a bespoke solution,
tailored specifically to the clients requirements, and as such of little
use to anyone else. Much of what the client used was in fact Free
Software (e.g. the LAMP stack). The engineering software comprised
several solutions from disparate vendors, including many embedded
systems for logging and monitoring equipment. The bit that I replaced
was over a decade old and unsuitable for the type of drilling work they
were about to do. In the mix of licenses was proprietary, BSD, GPL, and
others. At no point did I work on, or even witness, any Microsoft software.

And what does any of this have to do with my advocacy of Free Software?

Nothing.

Free Software is my preference. I'd very much like /all/ software to be
Free Software, and I advocate as much at every given opportunity. If it
were up to me then that would in fact be the way of things, but since I
am not ruler of planet earth I don't get to make that decision, and so I
must live and work in a world that is less than perfect, as do we all.

Living in an imperfect world, whilst wishing it could be better, is
*not* hypocrisy. Trying to *make* it a better world, is not hypocrisy.

